We must “build” the fixed‐asset “net” value by starting from the “initial” book value (taken from the “Initial… Fixed Assets” row) then adding any new fixed asset purchases (which are recorded with type “Fixed Assets Purchase”) and finally subtracting depreciation.

Step 1. Identify the beginning value:
• The “Initial20231231001” row with type “Fixed Assets” has an amount of 5000000.0.
  → Fixed assets net Initial Value = 5000000.00

Step 2. Identify all fixed asset additions (“Fixed Assets Purchase” transactions). In the table below there appear to be three such entries:
1. A row with id “FixedAsset20231231001” (first occurrence) with amount 516936.0 (asset “Processing Equipment4”).
2. Another “FixedAsset20231231001” row with amount 491117.63 (asset “Chemical Production Line5”).
3. A third “FixedAsset20231231001” row with amount 585150.04 (asset “Processing Equipment6”).

Compute the total purchased:
  516936.0 + 491117.63 = 1,008,053.63  
  1,008,053.63 + 585150.04 = 1,593,203.67

Step 3. Identify depreciation adjustments.
There is one depreciation row:
• Row “Depreciation20240101001” with an amount of 45751.04.  
So total depreciation = 45751.04

Step 4. Compute the net fixed assets at period‐end.
Start with the initial balance then add purchases and subtract depreciation:

  Net end value = 5000000.00 + 1,593,203.67 − 45,751.04  
  = 6,593,203.67 − 45,751.04  
  = 6,547,452.63

Thus, our answers are:

{
  "solution": {
    "fixed assets net Initial Value": "5000000.00",
    "fixed assets net End Value": "6547452.63"
  }
}
